This readmy provides information about syntax highlighting 
for X11-Basic for following different editors:

nedit           -- The Nirvana Editor (linux, WINDOWS)
920 Text Editor -- (Android)
vim             -- (linux, UNIX)
gedit / geany   -- (linux)       
nano            -- (linux)

For the text console I recommend to use nano, otherwise nedit, however
if you need UTF-8 support you may want to use gedit (and nano).

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
nedit.defs:

This is a macro package for nedit -- the Nirvana editor.


simply type

nedit -import nedit.defs 

and then save defaults. 

regards
Markus Hoffmann


================ INFORMATION ABOUT NEDIT ================================


Name        : nedit 
Version     : 5.3   
Group       : Productivity/Editors/Other
License     : GPL
URL         : http://nedit.org/
Summary     : Full featured, plain text Nirvana editor
Description :
NEdit is a GUI style plain text editor for workstations with the X
Window System and Motif. NEdit provides all of the standard menu,
dialog, editing, mouse support, macro extension language, syntax
highlighting, and a lot other nice features (and extensions for
programmers).

Authors:
--------
    Mark Edel <edel@fnal.gov>

======================== 902 Text Editor Syntax file =======================

920.conf

This is the syntax conf file for 920 Text Editor



======================== Vim syntax file ================================

Marcos Cruz has published a Vim syntax file:

http://programandala.net/en.program.x11-basic_vim_syntax_file

======================== gedit and geany sytax file ================================
x11basic.lang and x11basic.geany

I am sending you two files with syntax highlighting for X11 Basic for
gtksourceview (gedit) and geany. The geany version is a modified version of the
freebasic file because adding language support to geany is a nightmare, though
geany would have made a great ide for X11 Basic the syntax highlighting leaves a
lot to be desired. For gtksourceview you can copy the lang file to
/usr/share/gtksourceview3 and it will automatically be recognised. I believe
there is also an IDE that uses those definitions but I haven't used it.

Christos Tziotzis

======================== nano (and pico) sytax file ================================
x11basic.nanorc

Um das Syntax highlighting in Nano zu aktivieren, müssen die 
Konfigurationsdateien mit einer Profildatei aufgerufen werden.

nano ~/.nanorc

Soll nur für Shell Skripte das Syntax highlighting aktiviert werden, reicht es,
die entsprechende Konfigurationsdatei einzutragen.

include /usr/share/doc/x11basic/editors/x11basic.nanorc


